### Tested versions

- ~~Reproducible in all Godot versions from 4.2 onward (including current master).~~ 
- v4.3.stable.official [77dcf97d8] (tested only with godot-rust), 
- v4.5.stable.official [876b29033] (tested both with godot-cpp & godot-rust), 
- v4.6.dev.custom_build [c5f207fdc] (tested both with godot-cpp & godot-rust)

### System information

Any

### Issue description

Discovered during: https://github.com/godot-rust/gdext/issues/1404#issuecomment-3612088264

Long story short, given class:

<details>

<summary> Example runtime (non-tool) class </summary>

```cpp
class ExampleClass : public Node {
	GDCLASS(ExampleClass, Node)

protected:
	static void _bind_methods();

public:
	void _ready() override;
	ExampleClass() = default;
	~ExampleClass() override = default;
};

...

#include "example_class.h"

void ExampleClass::_bind_methods() {}

void ExampleClass::_ready() {
	print_line(vformat("Hello from editor!"));
	this->queue_free();
}

...

void initialize_gdextension_types(ModuleInitializationLevel p_level)
{
	if (p_level != MODULE_INITIALIZATION_LEVEL_SCENE) {
		return;
	}
	GDREGISTER_RUNTIME_CLASS(ExampleClass);
}
```

</details>

Executes its lifecycle methods (ready/process/anything) while created in any way other than proxing it via ClassDB:

<details>
<summary> Example in GDScript </summary>

```gdscript
func _ready() -> void:
	print("hello from script!")
	# Creates real, non-placeholder instance (which prints "hello from editor!" and frees itself imminently).
	var non_tool_node = ExampleClass.new()
	self.add_child(non_tool_node)
	non_tool_node.owner = get_tree().edited_scene_root

	# Creates placeholder instance (which stays in the scene).
	var non_tool_node2 = ClassDB.instantiate("ExampleClass")
	self.add_child(non_tool_node2)
	non_tool_node2.owner = get_tree().edited_scene_root
``` 
</details>

As far as I'm aware GDExtensions other than godot-cpp execute the same behavior as GDScript –   both interface methods `classdb_construct_object` and `classdb_construct_object2` explicitly return non-placeholder, "live" instance.

In Godot-cpp  (according https://github.com/godotengine/godot-cpp/issues/1552#issuecomment-2296698599):
- Using `memnew(T)` returns nullptr if used against non-tool (runtime) class.
- `ClassDBSingleton(...)instantiate("NonToolNode")` returns null object (correct me if I'm wrong). 

## Expected behavior

In GDscript both `MyClass.new()` and `ClassDB.instantiate("ExampleClass")` should return a placeholder, i.e. non-tool, runtime class should not run in the editor.

It is up to discussion what GDExtensions other than godot-cpp should do (I don't have any strong opinion – albeit expected behavior should be documented). Currently the only way to create the placeholder instance in GDExtension is via ClassDb singleton.

### Steps to reproduce

1) Set up a project according to https://github.com/godotengine/godot-cpp-template 
2) Declare your runtime, non-tool class:

example_class.h
```cpp
class ExampleClass : public Node {
	GDCLASS(ExampleClass, Node)

protected:
	static void _bind_methods();

public:
	void _ready() override;
	ExampleClass() = default;
	~ExampleClass() override = default;
};
```
example_class.cpp

```cpp
void ExampleClass::_bind_methods() {}

void ExampleClass::_ready() {
	print_line(vformat("Hello from editor!"));
	this->queue_free();
}
```

3) Create simple scene with a node as the root and attach following script to it:
```gdscript
@tool
extends Node


func _ready() -> void:
	print("Hello from script!")
	var example := ExampleClass.new()
	self.add_child(example)
	example.owner = self.get_tree().edited_scene_root

	var other_example = ClassDB.instantiate("ExampleClass")
	print(other_example)
	self.add_child(other_example)
	other_example.name = "Not a tool class"
	other_example.owner = self.get_tree().edited_scene_root
```

4) See the output – `Hello from editor!` is being print once, while placeholder named "Not a tool class" will be added as a child of the Node
```
Hello from script!
Hello from editor!
```

