### Tested versions

Reproducible in:

- Godot 4.5
- Godot 4.5 .NET

### System information

Linux Mint 22.2 - Godot v4.5 - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 2070 SUPER Mobile / Max-Q (TU104M)

### Issue description

When a Joint3D node or any of its parent nodes is hidden (by toggling visibility), the Joint3D gizmo remains visible in the viewport regardless. This behavior is demonstrated in the images below. While the example is simple, in complex assemblies this causes significant visual clutter and makes it difficult to select or manipulate the Joint3D node.

This issue was previously reported, and a working fix was submitted to the **joint_3d_gizmo_plugin.cpp** file, but the pull request was never merged. The following code change fully resolves the problem (verified in a custom build):

```
void Joint3DGizmoPlugin::incremental_update_gizmos() {
	if (!current_gizmos.is_empty()) {
		HashSet<EditorNode3DGizmo *>::Iterator E = current_gizmos.find(last_drawn);
		if (E) {
			++E;
		}
		if (!E) {
			E = current_gizmos.begin();
		}
		EditorNode3DGizmo *next_gizmo = *E;
		Node3D *node = next_gizmo->get_node_3d();
		if (node->is_visible_in_tree()) {
		    redraw(next_gizmo);
		}

		last_drawn = next_gizmo;
	}
}
```

